T1  - North-South trade and capital flows in a ricardian model of accumulation
AU  - Burgstaller, André
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
SP  - 241
EP  - 260
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(85)90054-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199685900546
AB  - A class-based, asymmetric general equilibrium model of the world economy is developed to trace the trajectory of the North-South terms of trade, the world profit rate, the Northern real wage, and the level of Southern employment in the presence of capital accumulation and technical progress. It is shown that (i) accumulation must be accompanied by a continuing deterioration in the terms of trade of the South and may entail a cumulative contraction in its level of employment; and (ii) technical progress in the South will of necessity produce a long-run worsening of its terms of trade and, assuming world demand for Southern goods is priceinelastic, of its level of unemployment.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Growth rates with an exhaustible resource and home goods
AU  - Moussavian, Mohammad
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
SP  - 281
EP  - 299
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(85)90056-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219968590056X
AB  - The growth path of an exhaustible resource exporting economy is examined. Previous work has shown that the size of the non-resource sector of such an economy may shrink to zero over time. This paper shows that this result hinges on the exclusion of the non-traded sector of the economy. With both traded and non-traded sectors included, the domestic interest rate may fluctuate more widely than the world interest rate, despite the results of previous work. Finally, the paper questions a ‘Dutch disease’ literature result: even when the industrial sector is more resource intensive than the service sector, it is possible for a faster growing resource price to have a ‘pro-industrialization’ effect.
ER  - 

