T1  - A two-country disequilibrium model
AU  - Owen, Robert F
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 18
IS  - 3
SP  - 339
EP  - 355
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(85)90059-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199685900595
AB  - The implications of wage and price rigidities for several open-economy macroeconomic questions are studied in a two-country framework, using comparative statics and numeric analytic solutions. In contrast to a small country disequilibrium approach, the proposed model highlights the critical dependence of trade balance stability and other comparative static results on the specification for the export rationing scheme. Although coordination of export rationing policies carries potential mutual benefits, it is shown that these may not be realized due to game-theoretic problems. The analysis also offers new illustrations and more general results which emphasize: (1) the dependence of the efficacy of macroeconomic policies on the specific set of wage and price rigidities as well as quantity constraints in both countries, and (2) the likelihood that a devaluation will have perverse trade balance effects in supply-constrained regimes.
ER  - 

